******
[2] 2 cities and 4 provinces
Date: Wed 17 Apr 2013
Source: English News, CCTV report [edited]
http://english.cntv.cn/program/china24/20130417/103581.shtml


China has confirmed 3 new cases of the H7N9 bird flu in Jiangsu Province, and 5 new cases in Zhejiang Province, bringing the total number of infections across the country to 71. One of the newly infected patients is in critical condition. So far, Beijing and Shanghai and 4 provinces of Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Anhui and Henan have reported bird flu infections. The death toll now stands at 14. The 7-year-old infection in Beijing can get out of the hospital Wed 17 Apr 2013.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

******
[3] Now 82 cases and 17 deaths
Date: Wed 17 Apr 2013
Source: China Daily, Xinhua report [edited]
http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013-04/17/content_16416736.htm


From 8 pm Tuesday to 5 pm Wednesday [16-17 Apr 2013], China confirmed 5 new cases of human H7N9 avian influenza infection, including one in Shanghai and 4 in Zhejiang province. The National Health and Family Planning Commission said in its daily update on H7N9 cases that a total of 82 H7N9 cases have been reported in China, including 17 that have ended in death. Of this total, 5 H7N9 patients have been discharged from hospitals after receiving treatment, and the other 60 patients are being treated in designated hospitals, according to the commission.

A total of 31 cases, including 11 that have ended in death, have been reported in Shanghai. 20 cases, including 3 deaths, have been reported in Jiangsu province, and 25 cases, including 2 deaths, in Zhejiang province. Anhui province has reported 3 cases, with one death. Beijing has reported one case, and 2 have been reported in Henan province.

China officially confirmed the occurrence of humans infected with the H7N9 virus late last month [March 2013].

According to the commission, China's confirmed H7N9 cases are isolated, and there has been no sign of human-to-human transmission.

