******
[4] Traditional Chinese medicine
Date: Wed 17 Apr 2013
Source: English News, Xinhua report [edited]
http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/china/2013-04/17/c_132317795.htm


Traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) has been used in the treatment of 24 of the 77 H7N9 cases reported across China as of Wednesday [17 Apr 2013], according to the State Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine.

Citing the case of a Beijing girl who was discharged from a hospital Wednesday [17 Apr 2013] afternoon, Liu Qingquan, a member of the TCM expert team for the prevention and control of human infections of H7N9, said at a press briefing that TCM was administered 15 hours after the patient took Western medicines when her temperature hit 39.8 C [103.64 F]. The patient began to sweat 3 hours later. After 5 hours, her temperature fell below 37.5 C [99.5]. She was also given other TCM remedies to ensure her bowel health.

Xu Zhiren, a senior official with the administration, said clinical practices have proven the outstanding effects of TCM when used at an early stage of an illness, and it also has a role to play in moderate and severe cases. According to Xu, the administration has set up a TCM emergency response system for public incidents, with 229 clinical bases established for the prevention and control of infectious diseases at provincial and city levels.

--
